issue.title: Create Modbus Devices for each listed connection point in Modbus configuration
issue.body:
### The problem

I've recently switched my Keba integration from the internal integration (based on unreliable UDP protocol) to Modbus TCP. So far this is far more stable and controllable, as TCP is stateful protocol. One thing that bothers me (and others: https://community.home-assistant.io/t/modbus-sensors-unique-id-and-device-support/373428) is, that we create a "device" in yaml, under which we place binary_sensors, sensors, switches, ...
If you then look in Settings - Devices, it only lists the sensors as entities, but does not list the "main" device. It would be cumbersome to have some correction of this. 
My config looks like this:

```
  - name: KEBAP30
    delay: 5
    timeout: 5
    type: tcp
    host: 192.168.1.102 # your callbox IP address goes here
    port: 502
    sensors:
      # Lesbare Sensoren
      - name: KebaP30_charging_state
        address: 1000
        scan_interval: 30
        data_type: uint32
        unique_id: KebaP30_charging_state
      - name: KebaP30_cable_state
        address: 1004
        scan_interval: 30
        data_type: uint32
        unique_id: KebaP30_cable_state

``` 

I would expect to see
- Device = KebaP30
   - Sensor: sensor.KebaP30_charging_state
   - Sensor: sensor.KebaP30_cable_state
  
I cannot fix this myself, but hope that you'll help the community and me. 
Many thanks. 

### What version of Home Assistant Core has the issue?

core-2024.10.1

### What was the last working version of Home Assistant Core?

_No response_

### What type of installation are you running?

Home Assistant OS

### Integration causing the issue

Modbus

### Link to integration documentation on our website

https://www.home-assistant.io/integrations/modbus

### Diagnostics information

_No response_

### Example YAML snippet

```yaml
- name: KEBAP30
    delay: 5
    timeout: 5
    type: tcp
    host: 192.168.1.102 # your callbox IP address goes here
    port: 502
    sensors:
      # Lesbare Sensoren
      - name: KebaP30_charging_state
        address: 1000
        scan_interval: 30
        data_type: uint32
        unique_id: KebaP30_charging_state
      - name: KebaP30_cable_state
        address: 1004
        scan_interval: 30
        data_type: uint32
        unique_id: KebaP30_cable_state
```


### Anything in the logs that might be useful for us?

_No response_

### Additional information

_No response_

issue.title: Medical Damage - 9mm underwhelming damage
issue.body:
<!--


I ACKNOWLEDGE THE FOLLOWING BEFORE PROCEEDING:
1. If I delete this entire template or parts of it and go my own path, the team may close my issue without further explanation or engagement.
2. If I list multiple bugs/concerns in this one issue, the team may close my issue without further explanation or engagement.
3. If I write an issue that has duplicates, the team may close my issue without further explanation or engagement (and without necessarily spending time to find the exact duplicate ID number).
4. If I leave the title incomplete when filing the issue, the team may close my issue without further explanation or engagement.
5. If I file something completely blank in the body, the team may close my issue without further explanation or engagement.
6. If I file an issue without collecting logs (RPT file, etc...), the team may close my issue without further explanation or engagement. 

All good? Then proceed and fill out the items below.
-->

**Mods (complete and add to the following information):**
- **Arma 3:** `2.20 stable` [e.g. 1.00 stable, rc,  dev]
- **CBA:** `3.18.4` [e.g. 3.0.0 stable, commit hash]
- **ACE3:** `3.20.0` [e.g. 3.0.0 stable, commit hash]
<!-- Make sure to reproduce the issue with only CBA and ACE3 on a newly created mission! -->

**Description:**
When using default medical settings, damage dealt with 9mm is unexpectedly low. A naked person will sometimes only be bruised from point-blank 9mm bullets.

A video demonstrating 9mm bruising unarmored targets from point-blank [was posted on Reddit](https://www.reddit.com/r/arma/comments/1mps3ry/can_someone_explain_why_9mm_only_causes_bruises/) by user u/Jean_Claude_Vacban, gaining hundreds of upvotes and a lot of comments of people sharing their similar experiences. *Note: a few comments were also made about body armor, but I shall make that into another issue.*

**Steps to reproduce:**
_Follow [this flowchart](https://ace3.acemod.org/img/wiki/user/issue_flowchart.webp)!_

1. Open 3den editor
2. Make sure you are on default ACE medical settings
3. Place down a player unit equipped with a 9mm pistol
4. Place down a target unit nearby without any armor (no uniform or headgear)
5. Enter preview
6. Fire the 9mm pistol at the limbs of the target
7. Observe semi-frequent low damage hits (bruises) to limbs

**Expected behavior:**
A 9mm pistol should cause considerable damage to unarmored targets at low ranges, with bruises being extremely rare.

**Where did the issue occur?**
- Editor (Singleplayer)

**Log Files:**
https://pastebin.com/xuDbQ66g

**Additional context:**
- YouTube video: https://youtu.be/XWS9Xn8Uhns

- Repro mission (used in the video): [ace_bodyarmor_test.Stratis.zip](https://github.com/user-attachments/files/21823024/ace_bodyarmor_test.Stratis.zip)

**Screenshots:**
If applicable, add screenshots to help explain your problem.

comment.body: Added a YouTube video of me reproducing the issue to the "additional context" section and attached a zip file to the mission where I did it.

The primary goal was to enhance code quality, maintainability, and testability by rigorously applying SOLID principles and Clean Code practices. The changes involve a complete overhaul of the internal architecture, breaking down complex functionalities into smaller, more focused, and interconnected components. This leads to a more robust and extensible codebase, making future development and debugging more efficient. ### Highlights * **Architectural Restructuring and Modularization**: The project's core logic has been extensively restructured, moving from a monolithic 'StressTestEngine' into a dedicated 'src/core' directory. This new structure introduces specialized classes like 'Compiler', 'Executor', 'FileManager', 'ResultManager', 'TestRunner', and 'WorkspaceManager', each with a single, well-defined responsibility. * **Application of SOLID Principles**: The refactoring heavily leverages interfaces (defined in 'src/core/interfaces.ts') and Dependency Injection. Classes like 'MyPanelProvider' and the new 'StressTestEngine' now receive their dependencies through their constructors, promoting loose coupling, testability, and adherence to the Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP). * **Enhanced Testability**: The addition of 'ts-mockito' as a development dependency, coupled with the new modular design, significantly improves the testability of the codebase. This allows for easier unit testing of individual components by mocking their dependencies. * **Improved Documentation**: A new 'GEMINI.md' file has been added, providing comprehensive documentation of the project's overview, features, architecture, and development conventions. Release notes

astro@5.13.2

Patch Changes

  • 4d16de7 Thanks @ematipico! - Improves the detection of remote paths in the _image endpoint. Now href parameters that start with // are considered remote paths.

  • Updated dependencies [4d16de7]:

    • @astrojs/markdown-remark@6.3.6

astro@5.13.1

Patch Changes

  • #14225 f2490ab Thanks @delucis! - Fixes the experimental.chromeDevtoolsWorkspace feature.

astro@5.13.0

Minor Changes

  • #14173 39911b8 Thanks @florian-lefebvre! - Adds an experimental flag staticImportMetaEnv to disable the replacement of import.meta.env values with process.env calls and their coercion of environment variable values. This supersedes the rawEnvValues experimental flag, which is now removed.

    Astro allows you to configure a type-safe schema for your environment variables, and converts variables imported via astro:env into the expected type. This is the recommended way to use environment variables in Astro, as it allows you to easily see and manage whether your variables are public or secret, available on the client or only on the server at build time, and the data type of your values.

    However, you can still access environment variables through process.env and import.meta.env directly when needed. This was the only way to use environment variables in Astro before astro:env was added in Astro 5.0, and Astro's default handling of import.meta.env includes some logic that was only needed for earlier versions of Astro.

    The experimental.staticImportMetaEnv flag updates the behavior of import.meta.env to align with Vite's handling of environment variables and for better ease of use with Astro's current implementations and features. This will become the default behavior in Astro 6.0, and this early preview is introduced as an experimental feature.

    Currently, non-public import.meta.env environment variables are replaced by a reference to process.env. Additionally, Astro may also convert the value type of your environment variables used through import.meta.env, which can prevent access to some values such as the strings "true" (which is converted to a boolean value), and "1" (which is converted to a number).

    The experimental.staticImportMetaEnv flag simplifies Astro's default behavior, making it easier to understand and use. Astro will no longer replace any import.meta.env environment variables with a process.env call, nor will it coerce values.

    To enable this feature, add the experimental flag in your Astro config and remove rawEnvValues if it was enabled:

    // astro.config.mjs
import { defineConfig } from "astro/config";

    export default defineConfig({

    • staticImportMetaEnv: true
      • 

    

      

    • rawEnvValues: false
      •

});

// src/components/MyComponent.astro
- const enabled: boolean = import.meta.env.ENABLED;

commits.message:
feat: Implement dynamic NVDEC decoder reconfiguration

This commit implements dynamic reconfiguration for the client-side NVDEC decoder to handle changes in video stream resolution.

The key changes are:
- Added `FrameDecoder::RecreateDecoder` to orchestrate the destruction and recreation of the decoder and its associated D3D12/CUDA resources.
- Implemented `FrameDecoder::DestroyDecoderResources` for safe and complete cleanup of all decoder-related resources.
- The `HandleVideoSequence` callback now detects format changes (resolution, chroma format, etc.) and triggers the reconfiguration process.
- When the decoder is reconfigured, the rendering and reordering queues are cleared to prevent artifacts from stale frames.
- The current `CUVIDEOFORMAT` is now stored in the `FrameDecoder` class to ensure accurate comparisons for detecting format changes.

This allows the client to seamlessly adapt when the server changes the streaming resolution, for example, after the client window is resized.

performed_via_github_app.description:
Amazon Q Developer is a generative AI assistant that enables you to automate code changes and legacy code transformation, all from a GitHub issue. After completing its code changes, Amazon Q Developer generates a pull request for your review. Start with 500 invocations per month of Amazon Q Developers feature development and code review capabilities and 10,000 lines of Java transformations per month. Increase your usage at any time by registering your Amazon Q Developer app installation with your AWS account.

# Feature development

Amazon Q Developer allows you to generate code directly from natural language prompts. You can build new features, debug, refine algorithms by describing your requests and letting Amazon Q Developer perform the tasks. It can help to save time, reduce errors, and improve efficiency with code generation that evolves with your project.

# Code transformation

Amazon Q Developer transforms outdated codebases into scalable, efficient, and maintainable systems. You can update your technology stack, enhance performance, and ensure future compatibility while preserving the core functionality of your existing code. With Amazon Q Developer, you can avoid technical debt and build your applications for long-term implications.

# Code review

With Amazon Q Developer, you can automate code reviews within GitHub. When Amazon Q Developer performs a code review, it analyzes your pull requests, provides feedback on code quality, potential issues, and security concerns. Amazon Q Developer then provides suggestions based on the code review.


# Getting started

1. Select the GitHub repositories that can use Amazon Q Developer and complete the authorization process.
2. Get started using Amazon Q Developer in an issue by adding labels for feature development or code transformation, or by creating a new pull request for code review.
